{"id":"2005.14453","submitter":"Tom Wettlin","authors":"Tom Wettlin, Talha Rahman, Jinlong Wei, Stefano Calabr\\`o, Nebojsa\n  Stojanovic and Stephan Pachnicke","title":"Complexity Reduction of Volterra Nonlinear Equalization for Optical\n  Short-Reach IM/DD Systems","comments":null,"journal-ref":"in Proc. 21th ITG-Symposium on Photonic Networks, pp. 65-70, Nov.\n  2020","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"eess.SP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We investigate approaches to reduce the computational complexity of Volterra\nnonlinear equalizers (VNLEs) for short-reach optical transmission systems using\nintensity modulation and direct detection (IM/DD). In this contribution we\nfocus on a structural reduction of the number of kernels, i.e. we define rules\nto decide which terms need to be implemented and which can be neglected before\nthe kernels are calculated. This static complexity reduction is to be\ndistinguished from other approaches like pruning or L1 regularization, that are\napplied after the adaptation of the full Volterra equalizer e.g. by\nthresholding. We investigate the impact of the complexity reduction on 90 GBd\nPAM6 IM/DD experimental data acquired in a back-to-back setup as well as in\ncase of transmission over 1 km SSMF. First, we show, that the third-order VNLE\nterms have a significant impact on the overall performance of the system and\nthat a high number of coefficients is necessary for optimal performance.\nAfterwards, we show that restrictions, for example on the tap spacing among\nsamples participating in the same kernel, can lead to an improved tradeoff\nbetween performance and complexity compared to a full third-order VNLE. We show\nan example, in which the number of third-order kernels is halved without any\nappreciable performance degradation.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 29 May 2020 08:51:26 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-01-08"}
