{"id":"2005.14590","submitter":"Andrew Hone N.W.","authors":"Andrew N.W. Hone and Juan Luis Varona","title":"Continued fractions for strong Engel series and L\\\"{u}roth series with\n  signs","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Acta Arithmetica, 2020","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.NT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  An Engel series is a sum of reciprocals $\\sum_{j\\geq 1} 1/x_j$ of a\nnon-decreasing sequence of positive integers $x_n$ with the property that $x_n$\ndivides $x_{n+1}$ for all $n\\geq 1$. In previous work, we have shown that for\nany Engel series with the stronger property that $x_n^2$ divides $x_{n+1}$, the\ncontinued fraction expansion of the sum is determined explicitly in terms of\n$z_1=x_1$ and the ratios $z_n=x_n/x_{n-1}^2$ for $n\\geq 2$. Here we show that,\nwhen this stronger property holds, the same is true for a sum $\\sum_{j\\geq\n1}\\epsilon_j/x_j$ with an arbitrary sequence of signs $\\epsilon_j=\\pm 1$. As an\napplication, we use this result to provide explicit continued fractions for\nparticular families of L\\\"{u}roth series and alternating L\\\"{u}roth series\ndefined by nonlinear recurrences of second order. We also calculate exact\nirrationality exponents for certain families of transcendental numbers defined\nby such series.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 29 May 2020 14:18:44 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 18 Oct 2020 10:10:45 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-11-11"}
